### ISSUE #3: Physical Housing: 3D-Printed Professor Figure Design and Assembly
Label: User story

**User Story:**
As a user, I want the Pocket Professor to have a compact and stable physical design so that it fits on my workspace and resembles a professor.

**Tasks:**
 - [ ] Research and select CAD software (FreeCAD, Fusion 360, or TinkerCAD)
 - [ ] Design the head component with a camera mount cavity in CAD
 - [ ] Design the body component with Raspberry Pi mounting points and ventilation holes
 - [ ] Design the base/legs to ensure the figure stands upright without support
 - [ ] Design optional aesthetic elements (arms, accessories like a coffee mug)
 - [ ] Add internal cable routing channels to the design
 - [ ] Export all design files to STL/OBJ format for printing
 - [ ] Test-print a prototype of one component to check fit and tolerances
 - [ ] Identify and correct any design issues found during test print
 - [ ] Print all full-scale body components (head, body, base)
 - [ ] Post-process printed parts (remove supports, sand, paint/finish as needed)
 - [ ] Assemble printed components using adhesive or fasteners
 - [ ] Mount Raspberry Pi and AI HAT 2 securely inside the body
 - [ ] Install camera in the head cavity and route cable internally
 - [ ] Secure microphone and speaker mounts inside the housing
 - [ ] Test that the completed figure stands upright and is structurally stable

Dependencies: Issue #1 (power system finalized), Issue #2 (camera dimensions known for head cavity).